[2]
From: "J.(Jan) A.M. Verhoeven" <jan.verhoeven@pi.net>
Organization: Foodfocus
Date: Sat, 17 May 1997 17:37:00 +0100
I am aware of the fact that ProMed is not intended to prevent outbreak of
diseases, but one can learn from the history.
Re: (drinking)watersafety
Any drinking water supplying system (old or new) should be (re-)DESIGNED to
be SAFE. Tubing which is no longer used should be removed immediately or
adapted to make free flowing possible.
In case of already occurred contamination or even dangerous situations the
following steps are to be taken:
-- 0) start with chlorination to control the risk. Be aware that the active
chlorine dose is still effective at those, sometimes far away places, where
the water is really used.
Cheap indicators are available for checking.
-- 1) Inspect the system for stagnation possibilities, (mixing)valves,
corrosion and build-up of chemical and organic origin. Special attention has
to be taken to prevent relative vacuum in the system (i.e. at moments where
at some place a great amount
of water is used). Exemple: suck up of waste water through hoses hanging in
dirty water is possible...!
-- 2) remove or clean and/or replace
-- 3) disinfect the sytem
-- 4) prevent contamination of the tubing system (UV disinfection etcetera)
The best way to organize these action is to do a thorough HACCP analysis. In
many cases you will conclude that there are lots of Critical Control Points.
In that case the system should be RE-designed in order to eliminate these
CCPs (build-in safety).
---
Jan Verhoeven
Foodfocus, consultancy- & servicebureau food: technology and qualityassurance
De Volder 32, NL-5383 ZD BOXTEL, The Netherlands
